<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="414" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,260,285]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Species with completely pale tibiae and tarsi except slightly brownish apical two tarsomeres in male, and three tarsomeres in female (
<figureCitation box="[592,662,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1989,2011]" captionTargetBox="[263,1310,209,1925]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[245,1320,193,1948]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 9. Merodon legionensis, male: a—abdomen, dorsal view (scale 1 mm); b—hind leg, lateral view (scale 0.5 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556019/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
b); mesoscutum covered with pale pile; shiny tergites, with goldenbronze reflection, covered with light yellowish hairs; tergites II and III in male with stripes of white microtrichia (
<figureCitation box="[159,227,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1989,2011]" captionTargetBox="[263,1310,209,1925]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[245,1320,193,1948]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 9. Merodon legionensis, male: a—abdomen, dorsal view (scale 1 mm); b—hind leg, lateral view (scale 0.5 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556019/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
a), contrary to related 
<taxonomicName box="[474,631,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Merodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">
<emphasis box="[474,631,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">M. flavicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[646,714,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1930,1952]" captionTargetBox="[151,1424,217,1895]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,193,1909]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 7. Merodon flavicornis, male: a—dorsal view (scale 1 mm); b—head, lateral view (scale 0.5 mm); c—hind leg, lateral view (scale 0.5 mm); d—head, anterior view (scale 0.5 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556017/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
a); eye pile in male black in upper 1/2 (in 
<taxonomicName box="[1182,1339,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Merodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">
<emphasis box="[1182,1339,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">M. flavicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
black in upper 1/3); pilosity on tergite V in female predominantly black (in 
<taxonomicName box="[894,1051,404,428]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Merodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">
<emphasis box="[894,1051,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">M. flavicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
pale); distribution restricted to the Iberian Peninsula.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,558,476,501]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Range and preferred habitat.</emphasis>
Iberian Peninsula (
<collectingCountry box="[785,851,476,501]" name="Spain" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Spain</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[911,1008,476,501]" name="Portugal" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Portugal</collectingCountry>
) (
<figureCitation box="[1034,1106,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,2009,2031]" captionTargetBox="[173,1397,1312,1970]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[173,1397,1312,1970]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Distribution of Merodon d flavicornis (●) and Merodon d legionensis (▲)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556016/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); open ground; unimproved, montane grassland, including open, grassy areas in pine forest or Mediterranean scrub, hedgehog heath, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rotundifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Quercus rotundifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
woodland (
<bibRefCitation author="Speight" box="[416,571,548,573]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Speight, M. C. D. (2016) Species accounts of European Syrphidae (Diptera), 2016. Syrph the Net, the database of European Syrphidae. Syrph the Net publications, Dublin, 93, 1 - 288." type="journal article" year="2016">Speight 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
